You probably mean:

    $slice = array_slice($array,$key-$count,**$key**+($count-1));

Just make sure you don&#39;t go negative:

    $key = 4;
    $count = 2;
    if ( ($key - $count) &lt; 0){
      $key = $count;
    }
    $slice = array_slice($array,$key-$count,$key+($count-1));

Erwin&#39;s answer is correct. 

If you also want to ensure the same number of values are selected if a key at the end of the array is given you will need to check for this:

    $key = 4;
    $count = 2;
    if ( ($key - $count) &lt; 0){
      $key = $count;
    } elseif ( ($key + $count) &gt; count($array) ) {
      $key = count($array) - $count;
    }
    $slice = array_slice($array,$key-$count,$key+($count-1));

Setting the offset to `$key - $count` is correct. You can use `max()` to keep it from going negative.

    $offset = max(0, $key - $count);

For the length, the basic calculation is `2 * $count + 1`. By adding `min($key - $count, 0)` to that, you can subtract any of the left-side count that would extend below zero.

    $length = 2 * $count + 1 + min($key - $count, 0);

You don&#39;t need to worry if the slice extends beyond the count of the array, that part will be ignored.

    $slice = array_slice($array, $offset, $length);

One way of doing this is to iterate over the objects to grab the rows and flatten them, then `reduce` over the arrays to aggregate them, finally using `Object.values` to get the correct dataset at the end. 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const data = [{ key: &#39;key1&#39;, rows: [ [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;1&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;5&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;4&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;2&quot;] ] }, { key: &#39;key1&#39;, rows: [ [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;10&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;50&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;40&quot;], [&quot;A&quot;, &quot;2018&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;20&quot;]]}];

    const key = data[0].key;

    // Use `flatMap` to iterate over the object and merge the rows
    const merged = data.flatMap(el =&gt; el.rows);

    const rows = Object.values(merged.reduce((acc, c) =&gt; {
      const [ k1, k2, k3, k4 ] = c;
      acc[k3] = acc[k3] || [ k1, k2, k3, 0 ];
      acc[k3][3] += +k4;
      return acc;
    }, {}));

    console.log([{ key, rows }]);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Note: if you need the aggregated number returned to a string simply map over the result:

    .map(([ a, b, c, d ]) =&gt; {
      return [ a, b, c, d.toString() ];
    });

#### Further reading

* [`flatMap`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/flatMap)
* [`reduce`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/Reduce)
* [`Object.values`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_objects/Object/values)

