Your code has a generic type named &quot;String&quot;  it&#39;s _valid_, but confusing.

From _&quot;Type Parameter Naming Conventions&quot;_ in [Generic Types](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/types.html) (my emphasis added below):

&gt; _**By convention, type parameter names are single, uppercase letters**. This stands in sharp contrast to the variable naming conventions that you already know about, and with good reason: **Without this convention, it would be difficult to tell the difference between a type variable and an ordinary class or interface name.**_

Also from that same reference:
```
The most commonly used type parameter names are:
E - Element (used extensively by the Java Collections Framework)
K - Key
N - Number
T - Type
V - Value
S,U,V etc. - 2nd, 3rd, 4th types
```

Following those conventions, your `PPrinter` class would look like this:
```
class PPrinter&lt;T&gt; {
    private T t;

    PPrinter(T t) {
        this.t = t;
    }

    T getT() {
        return this.t;
    }
}
```

You would still be able to call it with whatever type (`Integer`, `String`, `Boolean`, etc.) as your code also did, but without the confusion of your original question.
```
PPrinter&lt;Integer&gt; obj1 = new PPrinter&lt;&gt;(100);
PPrinter&lt;String&gt; obj2 = new PPrinter&lt;&gt;(&quot;foo&quot;);
PPrinter&lt;Boolean&gt; obj3 = new PPrinter&lt;&gt;(false);
```

